README FIRST
Read this notes carefully before you install or upgrade your database. Remember you have all needed information on your local system /usr/share/doc/mantis/ 

NEW INSTALLATION
* Database collation "UTF-8": releases Mantis 1.1.a2 and avobe now uses UTF-8 encoding by default on language files and encoding for database saved and read from the database.
The script installation set up the encoding UTF-8 for your new databases.
Be aware if you are using non-Latin characters on your database configuration and do not install before you ensure that will be work on your system. 
* User custom configuration: debian installation creates a custom file config_local.php, instead of editing config_inc.php directly. Everything you set on this file has precedence over settings defined in the config_inc.php 

UPGRADE INSTALLATION
* Backup before upgrading: - Always backup your database data before upgrading 
* Database collation "UTF-8": releases Mantis 1.1.a2 and avobe now uses UTF-8 encoding by default on language files and encoding for database saved and read from the database.
The script installation set up the encoding UTF-8 just for the newest creation information, do not update existing.
It highly recommended convert to UTF-8 your data information before upgrade. 
Read this information: Upgrading to a Mantis UTF8
Be aware if you are using non-Latin characters on your database configuration and do not install before you ensure that will be work on your system. 
* User custom configuration: debian installation maintains a custom file config_local.php, instead of editing config_inc.php directly. Everything you set on this file has precedence over settings defined in the config_inc.php 
* Upgrading:: Upgrades may take several minutes depending on the size of your database. 

Warning: When you finish the installation or upgrade process is is highly recommended to delete the admin directory.

Q: How to delete the admin directory?
Following mantis's apache2 configuration
the admin directory is located at 
/usr/share/mantis/www/admin
!!! The php pages in the admin directory can recreate, update, or erase the mantis database

#-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Installation process was complete! 

Continue to log into Mantis. 
You haved change the default 'administrator' email to: root@localhost 
You haved change the default 'administrator' password to: root 
Warning: When you finish the installation or upgrade process is is highly recommended to delete the admin directory.

Q: Where is the mantis login page?
Once mantis is installed correctly, go to
http://bugtracker.lynceantech.com/mantis/login_page.php

Q: First account to login?
user: administrator
password: root
!!! You need to change the default-account password immediately!

Q: Path?
Site Path /usr/share/mantis/www/
Core Path /usr/share/mantis/www/core/
Plugin Path /usr/share/mantis/www/plugins/              # <-- What is that?

Q: Mantis's apache configuration?
/etc/apache2/conf.d/mantis --> /etc/mantis/apache.conf

Q: How to go directly to mantis page?
To go from the default apache page to the mantis page, you will need to redirect it to 
http://<hostname>/mantis
To do that, in /var/www/index.html, add
<head>
<meta HTTP-EQUIV="REFRESH" content="0; url=http://www.yourdomain.com/index.html">
</head>

#-----------------------------------------------------------------------
# User creation

Q: Can you send emails from the mantis host?
Install sendEmail;  sudo apt-get install sendemail
sendemail -f emayssat@outlook.com -t emayssat@outlook.com -u SUBJECT -m MESSAGE -s localhost
!!! emails can be sent from aws.amazon.com to outlook.com


Q: To create your first account account?
Login as an administrator (administrator / root)
Go to the manage tab
Select manage user
Create the first account emayssat as administrator

Q: How to remove the warning at the login page?
Change the password of the initial administrator account!!!
This is down for security 

Q: How to create your second, third account?


Q: How to set, change a user password?
mysql -u root -p
use bucktracker;
update mantis_user_table set password=md5('password') where username='username';
